	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Will high world food prices persist?</h1>

			
			<h4>
												01 March 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to Lester Brown, a prominent food pundit, the all-time high recorded by the UN FAO food price index in December 2010 is not an isolated peak caused solely by last year’s drought in Russia and floods in Pakistan. The index, which tracks a basket of key commodities, rose to 215 points. According to FAO, the ‘global food system is becoming more vulnerable and susceptible to episodes of extreme price volatility’. Although prices for nearly all food commodities have risen, the sharpest increases were concentrated in sugar and vegetable oil.</p><p>&nbsp;‘Whereas in years past,’ Brown writes, ‘it’s been weather that has caused a spike in commodities prices, now it’s trends on both sides of the food supply/demand equation that are driving up prices.’ On the demand side, ‘the culprits are population growth, rising affluence, and the use of grain to fuel cars.’ Total meat consumption in China, according to Brown, is already nearly double that in the USA. Longer-term supply-side issues also remain a problem. These include soil erosion, aquifer depletion, urban encroachment on cropland and water supplies, stalling of the formerly inexorable rise of crop yields in developed countries, heat waves, and melting mountain glaciers and ice-sheets. Climate change will exacerbate some of these.</p><p>Much of this analysis is widely shared. WTO Director-General Pascal Lamy has quoted, with approval, projections from the OECD and FAO that by 2019, if current biofuel policies continue, about 13% of the global production of coarse grains will be used for ethanol, 16% of vegetable oil, and 35% of sugar cane. But as contributory factors to the current price rises, he adds export restrictions (notably those in Russia and Ukraine) and other trade barriers such as tariffs and subsidies, which prevent food from being produced where this can be most efficiently done. Mr Lamy has argued that the way ahead is on the one hand, to remove trade barriers that prevent efficient agricultural markets from emerging (by re-energising the Doha Development Round) and, on the other, to provide ‘more social safety nets, more food aid and possibly food reserves’.</p><p>Meanwhile, World Bank President Robert Zoellick has argued that ‘free markets can still feed the world’, with the poor securing access to sufficient food if:</p>
<ul>

<li>‘public access to information on the quality and quantity of grain stocks’ is increased;</li>

<li>‘long-range weather forecasting and monitoring’ is improved;</li>

<li>‘our understanding of the relationship between international prices and local prices in poor countries’ is deepened;</li>

<li>‘small regional humanitarian reserves in disaster-prone, infrastructure-poor areas’ are established under WFP management;</li>

<li>agreement is reached on ‘a code of conduct to exempt humanitarian food aid from export bans’;</li>

<li>effective social safety-nets are established;</li>

<li>fast-disbursing support instruments are established as an alternative to export bans or price fixing;</li>

<li>‘a robust menu of other risk management products’ is developed;</li>

<li>smallholder farmers are helped to become ‘a bigger part of the solution to food security’.</li>

</ul>
<p>Mr Zoellick maintains that ‘the answer to food price volatility is not to prosecute or block markets, but to use them better.’</p><p>A rather different prescription has been offered by President Sarkozy. Blaming financial speculation rather than fundamentals for contributing to soaring commodity prices, he has asked from his platform as current president of the Group of 20, ‘How can you explain that we regulate money markets and not commodities?’ Following the lead already taken by the US, Europe has made proposals that would force traders to disclose their positions, put a cap on large trades and give regulators new powers to intervene to curb speculation. But there are reported to be deep divisions within the broader G20 on how far any new global regulations should go. ‘It’s going to be difficult to have a global consensus on position limits until the case is better made,’ a G20 source told Reuters after Sarkozy spoke.</p>
		
		
