				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Sharp increases in food prices have political consequences, as recent events in North Africa have underlined dramatically. ACP states as poor, mainly agricultural economies are very heavily influenced by both political and natural events on the global stage. Both their agricultural and their trade strategies need to be acutely sensitive to the shocks that the global market may produce – and the possibility that these are likely to change in the future.</p><p>It has been clear for some time that the periodic cycles in the supply of basic food to the world market are occurring around a rising secular price trend. Some of the demand-side determinants of the underlying trend are unlikely to be reversed (such as the growth in Asian demand). Others, such as the competition between food and biofuels and restrictions on boosting yields through biotechnology, may change. On the supply side, climate change is ‘the elephant in the room’ for many ACP states. It has the potential to wreak havoc with current farming methods in some ACP countries, thus robbing those states of a significant source of foreign exchange from exports just at the time that they become more dependent on imports to feed their people.</p><p>What the 2008 and 2010 price spikes add to this knowledge of underlying trends is FAO’s claim that the global food system is now more vulnerable to ‘episodes of extreme price volatility’. International actions as suggested by Pascal Lamy for food aid and strategically placed reserves, and Robert Zoellick’s call for a greater role to be given to smallholder farmers in meeting the food security challenge, may become increasingly vital if widespread hunger is to be avoided.</p>
		</div>
		
